## 2. Ground Truth / Label Generation

PLACEHOLDER. Describe how the supervision or reference signal is produced: where it comes from, how it is generated or annotated, and any synthesis or augmentation applied. State the assumptions that, if wrong, would invalidate every result, because this is the most common silent source of error. If labels are generated programmatically, name the exact procedure so a {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} can reproduce them bit for bit.

Checklist: (a) source of truth named; (b) generation or annotation procedure reproducible; (c) the assumption that would invalidate results stated explicitly; (d) known label noise or measurement error quantified or flagged.

Example (illustrative): a perception project labels objects with a heuristic auto-labeler, then hand-audits 200 frames; the stated assumption is "auto-labels agree with human labels above 95 percent on the audited slice." If a {{EXPERIMENT_UNIT_LABEL}} regresses, re-checking this assumption comes before blaming the model.

## 3. Objective / Criterion Design

PLACEHOLDER. Describe the objective the method optimizes or the criterion that decides success: the loss, score, or acceptance rule, what it rewards and penalizes, and its known failure modes (for example, an imbalance that lets a trivial solution score well). Record the currently accepted objective here; record rejected objective variants in `docs/method/algorithmic-levers.md` section 3.

Stress-test the objective by asking what the laziest solution that maximizes it looks like. If that solution is useless (predict the majority class, return the cached answer, report the control wells), the objective needs a guard or a counter-metric in `docs/evaluation/evaluation-and-visualization.md` section 1.

Example (illustrative): an imbalanced classification objective lets "always predict negative" score 0.95 accuracy. The guard is to track per-class recall as a counter-metric, so the trivial solution is visibly rejected even when headline accuracy looks high.

